Date:8/1/2011 10:51:37 AM
From:Mr.Gogo
I have a question for the community. If a stock is being traded on two
exchnges, how does the correction of the price works? For example today Cameco
on NYSE CCJ is +0.19 and the same company on TSE: CCO is -2%
USD is negligibly up against the CAD? Would be very glad if anyone has
explanation.

Thanks, Geori
%EOM----------------------

%BOM---------------------
Date:8/1/2011 11:11:59 AM
From:Difco
Hi Georgi,

The NYSE listing is a sponsored ADR, meaning Cameco's shares are held by the
depository bank and Cameco has a direct involvement in the issuance of the
receipts. Usually, the correction would occur through arbitrage of the shares -
selling the overvalued and buying the undervalued. This could be done by
regular investors or sometimes the depository bank (Bank of New York Mellon is
the largest) could do it - think of BRK/B shares which are trading at a
fraction of BRK/A as the depository bank keeps them in check.

Difco
%EOM----------------------

